<subSubSection id="C34D655F0703FFDFFF4CFC12FF60AF34" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF4CFC12FDCEA9F9" blockId="5.[170,589,976,1003]" box="[170,589,976,1003]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
<heading id="D0A081B80703FFDFFF4CFC12FDCEA9F9" box="[170,589,976,1003]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFF4CFC12FDCEA9F9" authority="A. Agassiz, 1863" authorityName="A. Agassiz" authorityYear="1863" box="[170,589,976,1003]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFF4CFC12FE17A9F9" bold="true" box="[170,404,976,1003]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Diadema mexicanum</emphasis>
A. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B250703FFDFFE5CFC12FDCEA9F9" author="AGASSIZ A." box="[442,589,976,1002]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" pagination="352 - 360" refId="ref8890" refString="AGASSIZ A. 1863. - Synopsis of the echinoids collection on the Pacific exploring expedition. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 15: 352 - 360." type="journal article" year="1863">Agassiz, 1863</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF97FBCDFF60AF34" blockId="5.[113,647,1039,1700]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFEE0FBD2FE21AE3A" authorityName="A. Agassiz" authorityYear="1863" box="[262,418,1040,1065]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFEE0FBD2FE21AE3A" box="[262,418,1040,1065]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
studied in this investigation were collected from the Galapagos Islands, and from Acapulco, Mazatlan and Pochutla in 
<collectingRegion id="4993F8360703FFDFFF97FBACFF45AE9B" box="[113,198,1134,1160]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Mexico</collectingRegion>
. Adult specimens had a mean horizontal test diameter of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFEC8FB4CFE02AEBA" box="[302,385,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="75.0">75 mm</quantity>
(SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFE3CFB4CFDB4AEBA" box="[474,567,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="6.1">6.1 mm</quantity>
) and a mean vertical diameter of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFE6EFB6CFE55AEDB" box="[392,470,1198,1224]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
(SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFDC7FB6CFDF8AEDB" box="[545,635,1198,1224]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
). Maximum test diameters of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFE51FB0CFD89AEFB" box="[439,522,1230,1256]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="92.0">92 mm</quantity>
(h.d.) and 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310703FFDFFF97FB2FFF47AF1B" box="[113,196,1261,1288]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" unit="mm" value="46.0">46 mm</quantity>
(v.d.) were recorded from 
<specimenCount id="9D51FD5D0703FFDFFE17FB2FFD04AF14" box="[497,647,1261,1287]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" type="generic">48 specimens</specimenCount>
examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34D655F0703FFDFFF6EFAEFFC36AE39" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF6EFAEFFCB9ABFC" blockId="5.[113,647,1039,1700]" lastBlockId="5.[677,1210,216,1066]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
As reported by H. L. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B250703FFDFFE89FAEFFE7DAF54" author="CLARK H. L." box="[367,510,1325,1351]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" pagination="225 - 352" refId="ref9323" refString="CLARK H. L. 1948. - A report on the echini of the warmer eastern Pacific, based on the collections of the Velero III. Allan Hancock Pacific Expeditions 8 (5): 225 - 352." type="journal article" year="1948">Clark (1948)</bibRefCitation>
, the test was black with a brown tinge. The patterns of iridophores were similar to those seen in 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFE12FAAFFD05AF95" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[500,646,1388,1414]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFE12FAAFFD05AF95" box="[500,646,1388,1414]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFF78FA4EFEA9AFB6" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1909" box="[158,298,1420,1445]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFF78FA4EFEA9AFB6" box="[158,298,1420,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, like 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFE2AFA4EFDDBAFB6" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1909" box="[460,600,1420,1445]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFE2AFA4EFDDBAFB6" box="[460,600,1420,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the blue colour was not bold or distinct. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B250703FFDFFDF6FA6EFF38AFF6" author="MORTENSEN T." pageId="5" pageNumber="98" refId="ref9794" refString="MORTENSEN T. 1940. - Monograph of the Echinoidea. III (1). C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 370 p." type="book" year="1940">Mortensen (1940)</bibRefCitation>
correctly reported the presence of faint blue lines that proceeded from each side of the genital pore down to the ambitus where they bisected the naked median areas. These faint parallel lines were not always continuous, with the presence of small side branches between secondary spines. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B250703FFDFFDF2F9A8FF38ACB0" author="MORTENSEN T." pageId="5" pageNumber="98" refId="ref9794" refString="MORTENSEN T. 1940. - Monograph of the Echinoidea. III (1). C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 370 p." type="book" year="1940">Mortensen (1940)</bibRefCitation>
also reported that there were no white spots in the adapical naked interambulacral area. Obvious white spots were not typically seen on specimens during the day. However, at night distinct white spots with faint white lines were seen leading from the naked median areas to the genital pores. These features were visible on the denuded test of some specimens (
<figureCitation id="136C2A510703FFDFFCFDFE54FCEBABA3" box="[795,872,406,432]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[113,124,861,878]" captionTargetBox="[188,1134,215,816]" captionTargetId="figure-46@6.[472,756,473,559]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 2. — A-I, photographs of the median areas of the interambulacra, showing the variation in characters that occur: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. mexicanum; C, D, D. savignyi; E, D. setosum; F, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); G, E. calamaris (white colour morph); H, E. diadema; I, D. palmeri; J, D. palmeri (whole specimen). Scale bars: A-I, 5 mm; J, 50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401712/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
, faint white marking surrounded by area of darker pigment), but were not visible on all specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFD5DFE37FB8AA89D" blockId="5.[677,1210,216,1066]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
The shape of the test was distinctly rounded pentagonal rather than horizontally circular and more flattened in appearance than 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFBF9FDF7FB31A85D" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[1055,1202,564,590]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFBF9FDF7FB31A85D" box="[1055,1202,564,590]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The ambulacra measured 25-30% of the interambulacra measured at the ambitus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFD5DFD51FBF0A9F9" blockId="5.[677,1210,216,1066]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
The apical system (
<figureCitation id="136C2A510703FFDFFC9CFD51FC4BA8BE" box="[890,968,659,685]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) was slightly depressed, hemicyclic and measured 20-25% of the test’s horizontal diameter. The periproct measured 12-16% (h.d.) and was black with a small anal cone. The genital plates (
<figureCitation id="136C2A510703FFDFFCA1FCD0FC1FA93F" box="[839,924,786,812]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) were similar in shape to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFCE2FCF1FC1AA95F" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[772,921,818,844]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFCE2FCF1FC1AA95F" box="[772,921,818,844]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, they had fewer tubercles (between zero and two) while the genital pores were typically larger. Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFBC9FCB0FB21A998" authorityName="Michelin" authorityYear="1845" box="[1071,1186,882,907]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFBC9FCB0FB21A998" box="[1071,1186,882,907]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a distinct arch-shaped depression was present on the genital plates in both juveniles and adults, forming the corners of the pentamerous apical ring.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFD5DFC32FC36AE39" blockId="5.[677,1210,216,1066]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">The peristome was deep brown in colour and measured 45-50% (h.d.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
